I keep telling myself to stay calm and take deep breaths. I can't afford to panic right now. My eyes scan around the station to see if there's anything else I could do.[l][r]
There she is. My wife, barreling down the hall with the AED. I rush over to her.[r]
Taking the small device, I race back and kneel by Chito's side.[l][r]
Ms. Ishii pulled away from the third round of rescue breaths, her eyes misty and sweat running down her forehead.[l][r]
She's methodically following the procedure, too focused to do anything else — like wiping off her streaming tears. She probably doesn't even realize she's crying.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

[cm  ]
[tb_start_text mode=3 ]
"I'm... going to use the AED. Please, ask everyone to stay back."[r]
"Understood."[l][r]
I'm doing what needs to be done. I ask my wife to take over for Ms. Ishii if she gets tired, then start to clear the gathering crowd.[l][r]
[_tb_end_text]

